The mv command in Linux is used to move or rename files and directories. It‚Äôs one of the most commonly used file management commands.

sysadmin@localhost:~$ cd ~/Documents

sysadmin@localhost:~/Documents$ mv people.csv Work

sysadmin@localhost:~/Documents$ ls Work                                         
people.csv
(The file will keep its name if you don't specify a new name)

mv can be used for a lot of files as long as the last argument is the destination:

sysadmin@localhost:~/Documents$ mv numbers.txt letters.txt alpha.txt School        
sysadmin@localhost:~/Documents$ ls School                                       
Art  Engineering  Math  alpha.txt  letters.txt  numbers.txt 

*moving a file to the same directory is another way of changing its name:

mv animals.txt zoo.txt

*****

* rm : this command is used to delete files and directories

* rm by default, rm ignores (actually refuses to remove) directories.

To remove directories with rm, you need specific options:

-r or --recursive: remove directories and their contents recursively
rm -r mydir

-rf: same as above, but force removal without confirmation
rm -rf mydir


**

The grep command is one of the most commonly used tools in Unix/Linux systems ‚Äî it‚Äôs used to search for text patterns inside files or output.

grep [options] PATTERN [FILE...]
PATTERN ‚Üí what you‚Äôre searching for (a word, phrase, or regex)

FILE ‚Üí the file(s) to search in

Examples:
1. Search for a word in a file
grep "hello" file.txt

2. Ignore case
grep -i "hello" file.txt

3. Show line numbers
grep -n "hello" file.txt

4. Search recursively in directories
grep -r "main()" src/

5. Show only filenames that contain matches
grep -l "TODO" *.py

6. Invert match (show lines without the pattern)
grep -v "error" log.txt

7. Use regular expressions
grep -E "cat|dog" animals.txt



| Pattern | Meaning                                 | Example                  | Description                             |                                         |                                   |
| ------- | --------------------------------------- | ------------------------ | --------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------- | --------------------------------- |
| `.`     | Any single character                    | `gr.p`                   | Matches ‚Äúgrep‚Äù, ‚Äúgrap‚Äù, ‚Äúgr1p‚Äù          |                                         |                                   |
| `^`     | Start of line                           | `^Hello`                 | Matches lines beginning with ‚ÄúHello‚Äù    |                                         |                                   |
| `$`     | End of line                             | `world$`                 | Matches lines ending with ‚Äúworld‚Äù       |                                         |                                   |
| `[]`    | Character set                           | `gr[ae]y`                | Matches ‚Äúgray‚Äù or ‚Äúgrey‚Äù                |                                         |                                   |
| `[^ ]`  | Negated set                             | `gr[^a]y`                | Matches ‚Äúgrey‚Äù but not ‚Äúgray‚Äù           |                                         |                                   |
| `*`     | 0 or more of previous char              | `go*gle`                 | Matches ‚Äúggle‚Äù, ‚Äúgogle‚Äù, ‚Äúgoogle‚Äù, etc. |                                         |                                   |
| `+`     | 1 or more of previous char *(use `-E`)* | `go+gle`                 | Matches ‚Äúgogle‚Äù, ‚Äúgoogle‚Äù               |                                         |                                   |
| `?`     | 0 or 1 of previous char *(use `-E`)*    | `colou?r`                | Matches ‚Äúcolor‚Äù or ‚Äúcolour‚Äù             |                                         |                                   |
| `       | `                                       | Alternation *(use `-E`)* | `cat                                    | dog`                                    | Matches lines with ‚Äúcat‚Äù or ‚Äúdog‚Äù |
| `()`    | Grouping *(use `-E`)*                   | `(cat                    | dog)s?`                                 | Matches ‚Äúcat‚Äù, ‚Äúcats‚Äù, ‚Äúdog‚Äù, or ‚Äúdogs‚Äù |                                   |


**The simplest one using the literal expression

sysadmin@localhost:~/Documents$ grep sysadmin passwd                               
sysadmin:x:1001:1001:System Administrator,,,,:/home/sysadmin:/bin/bash

**
'root'
the single quotes (' ') around root are just a way to quote the search pattern ‚Äî they aren‚Äôt part of the pattern itself

//You want to prevent the shell from interpreting something before grep sees it//

sysadmin@localhost:~/Documents$ grep 'root' passwd
root:x:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash                                                 
operator:x:1000:37::/root:

**
sysadmin@localhost:~/Documents$ grep '^root' /etc/passwd
root:x:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash

^ first character of the pattern

** 'r$' makes sure the pattern is at the end
sysadmin@localhost:~/Documents$ grep 'r$' alpha-first.txt
B is for Bear
F is for Flower


** .
It shows any coincidence that stars with r and ends by f, no matter which letters are in the middle.

sysadmin@localhost:~/Documents$ grep 'r..f' red.txt
reef
roof

It shows 4 character results:
sysadmin@localhost:~/Documents$ grep '....' red.txt                             
