Visualizing processes

User who have admin rights can manage any process of any user, even stop any process.

ps : This command can be use to see the processes.

sysadmin@localhost:~$ ps
  PID TTY          TIME CMD
   80 pts/0        00:00:00 bash
   94 pts/0        00:00:00 ps

| Column    | Description                                        |
| --------- | -------------------------------------------------- |
| **UID**   | User who owns the process                          |
| **PID**   | Process ID (unique per running process)            |
| **PPID**  | Parent Process ID (the process that started it)    |
| **C**     | CPU usage percentage                               |
| **STIME** | Start time                                         |
| **TTY**   | Terminal associated with the process (`?` if none) |
| **TIME**  | Total CPU time used                                |
| **CMD**   | The command that launched the process              |




| Command  | Meaning                                                  | Example Output                         |
| -------- | -------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------- |
| `ps`     | Shows processes **in the current shell**                 | Usually just `bash`, maybe `ps` itself |
| `ps -e`  | Show **all** processes on the system                     | Every process from all users           |
| `ps -f`  | ‚ÄúFull format‚Äù ‚Äî adds more columns                        | UID, PID, PPID, CMD                    |
| `ps -ef` | Show **every process in full detail**                    | Most common form on Linux              |
| `ps aux` | BSD-style syntax; shows all processes with CPU/mem usage | Another popular variant                |


if you use ps -e

sysadmin@localhost:~$ ps -e
  PID TTY          TIME CMD                                                     
    1 pts/0        00:00:00 init                                                    
   33 ?            00:00:00 rsyslogd                                                
   37 ?            00:00:00 cron                                                    
   39 ?            00:00:00 sshd                                                    
   56 ?            00:00:00 named                                                   
   69 pts/0        00:00:00 login                                                   
   79 pts/0        00:00:00 bash                                                    
   94 pts/0        00:00:00 ps 



ps -ef
it can show you more detailed results

sysadmin@localhost:~$ ps -ef
UID        PID  PPID  C STIME TTY          TIME CMD                             
