--*
apt-get install can also be used to update a package if it's already installed. 


1. Use apt-get update to update the package cache.

2. use apt-get upgrade to update all packages with their dependencies.

sysadmin@localhost:~$ sudo apt-get update                                       
[sudo] password for sysadmin:                                                   
Ign file: amd64/ InRelease                                                      
Ign file: amd64/ Release.gpg                                                    
Ign file: amd64/ Release                                                        
Reading package lists... Done                                                   
sysadmin@localhost:~$ sudo apt-get upgrade                                      
Reading package lists... Done                                                   
Building dependency tree                                                        
Reading state information... Done                                               
Calculating upgrade... Done                                                     
0 upgraded, 0 newly installed, 0 to remove and 0 not upgraded.

--
An admin can run this command apt-get remove to remove a package 
or 
apt-get purge  to purge a package completely from the system.


*********************
UPDATING USER'S PASSWORDS:

* passwd 
it's used to update a user's password.

sysadmin@localhost:~$ passwd                                                    
Changing password for sysadmin.                                                 
(current) UNIX password: netlab123                                                       
Enter new UNIX password:                                                       
Retype new UNIX password:                                                       
passwd: password updated successfully

*If the user wants to see the password's information, they can use the option -S

sysadmin@localhost:~$ passwd -S sysadmin                                       
sysadmin P 12/20/2017 0 99999 7 -1


| Field          | Meaning              | Explanation                                                                                     |
| -------------- | -------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **sysadmin**   | Username             | The account name queried.                                                                       |
| **P**          | Password status      | `P` = Password is **set** (active). <br>`L` = Locked. <br>`NP` = No password.                   |
| **12/20/2017** | Last password change | Date when the password was last changed.                                                        |
| **0**          | Minimum days         | Minimum number of days between password changes (0 = can change anytime).                       |
| **99999**      | Maximum days         | Maximum number of days the password is valid before it must be changed (99999 ‚âà no expiration). |
| **7**          | Warning period       | Days before expiration when the user is warned to change the password.                          |
| **-1**         | Inactive period      | Days after password expiration that the account remains active (-1 = never expires).            |


****
Redirecting:

Redirection means changing the default input or output streams of a command.
By default:
Standard input (stdin) ‚Üí your keyboard
Standard output (stdout) ‚Üí your terminal
Standard error (stderr) ‚Üí your terminal


| FD    | Name     | Stream          | Description                             |
| ----- | -------- | --------------- | --------------------------------------- |
| **0** | `stdin`  | Standard Input  | Keyboard input or input redirection.    |
| **1** | `stdout` | Standard Output | Normal program output (e.g., terminal). |
| **2** | `stderr` | Standard Error  | Error messages and diagnostics.         |




In this section we're gonna use STDOUT.

sysadmin@localhost:~/Documents$ cat food.txt > newfile1.txt
sysadmin@localhost:~/Documents$ cat newfile1.txt         
Food is good.     
sysadmin@localhost:~/Documents$ echo "I like food." > newfile1.txt
sysadmin@localhost:~/Documents$ cat newfile1.txt             
I like food.  

to make sure you don't overwrite the file you can use double >> 

sysadmin@localhost:~/Documents$ echo "This food is good." >> newfile1.txt
sysadmin@localhost:~/Documents$ cat newfile1.txt              
I like food.                                                      
This food is good.      

**************

TEXT EDITOR:

vi is the text editor used in Linux. Some distributions might no use vi but an improved version called: vim.
to create a new file

sysadmin@localhost:~$ vi newfile.txt

At first, you'll see there's a command screen. It is used to write commands, like the ones used for going over the document,
manipulate the text and access other modes. To come back to the command mode anytime, press the ESC key.

| Action                       | Command       | Description                            |
| ---------------------------- | ------------- | -------------------------------------- |
| Move left                    | `h`           | Move the cursor left                   |
| Move right                   | `l`           | Move the cursor right                  |
| Move up                      | `k`           | Move the cursor up                     |
| Move down                    | `j`           | Move the cursor down                   |
| Delete a character           | `x`           | Deletes the character under the cursor |
| Undo last change             | `u`           | Undo                                   |
| Redo last undo               | `Ctrl + r`    | Redo                                   |
| Copy (yank) a line           | `yy`          | Copy current line                      |
| Paste                        | `p`           | Paste after cursor                     |
| Cut (delete) a line          | `dd`          | Delete current line                    |
| Move to start of line        | `0`           | Jump to the beginning of the line      |
| Move to end of line          | `$`           | Jump to the end of the line            |
| Search text                  | `/text`       | Search forward for ‚Äútext‚Äù              |
| Save file                    | `:w`          | Write (save) file                      |
| Quit Vim                     | `:q`          | Quit Vim                               |
| Save and quit                | `:wq` or `ZZ` | Save and quit                          |
| Force quit (discard changes) | `:q!`         | Quit without saving                    |


Standard	Vi	Meaning
cut	d	 (delete)
copy	y	copy (yank)
paste	P | p	put (put)


| Action                     | Command          | Description                                   |
| -------------------------- | ---------------- | --------------------------------------------- |
| Cut a line                 | `dd`             | Deletes (cuts) the current line               |
| Cut 3 lines                | `3dd`            | Deletes (cuts) 3 lines starting at the cursor |
| Cut a word                 | `dw`             | Deletes (cuts) a word                         |
| Cut to end of line         | `d$`             | Deletes (cuts) from cursor to end of line     |
| Cut text visually selected | `v` + move + `d` | Visually select text, then delete it          |
| Cut three next words       | `d3w`            | Deletes (cuts) from cursor to end of line     |
| Cut four characters of the left | `d4h`       | Visually select text, then delete it          |


| Command | Motion        | Effect                  | Mode   |
| ------- | ------------- | ----------------------- | ------ |
| `cc`    | (entire line) | Change whole line       | Insert |
| `cw`    | word          | Change word             | Insert |
| `c3w`   | 3 words       | Change 3 words          | Insert |
| `c5h`   | 5 chars left  | Change 5 chars backward | Insert |



| Action                      | Command          | Description                       |
| --------------------------- | ---------------- | --------------------------------- |
| Copy a line                 | `yy`             | Copies current line               |
| Copy 3 lines                | `3yy`            | Copies 3 lines                    |
| Copy a word                 | `yw`             | Copies word from cursor           |
| Copy to end of line         | `y$`             | Copies from cursor to end of line |
| Copy visually selected text | `v` + move + `y` | Select text, then yank it         |


| Command | Meaning                                                 |
| ------- | ------------------------------------------------------- |
| `p`     | Paste **after** the cursor (or below the current line)  |
| `P`     | Paste **before** the cursor (or above the current line) |


****
Basic Searching in vi

Forward Search
/pattern

Backward Search
?pattern


Insert mode (Normal Mode)

| Command | Meaning                                | Cursor Position After               |
| ------- | -------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------- |
| `i`     | Insert before the cursor               | Before current character            |
| `I`     | Insert at the beginning of the line    | Start of line                       |
| `a`     | Append after the cursor                | After current character             |
| `A`     | Append at the end of the line          | End of line                         |
| `o`     | Open a new line **below** current line | At start of new line                |
| `O`     | Open a new line **above** current line | At start of new line                |
| `cw`    | Change (replace) word                  | Deletes word and enters insert mode |
| `cc`    | Change (replace) whole line            | Deletes line and enters insert mode |




EX MODE


| Command         | Description                                                         |
| --------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `:w`            | Save (write) the file                                               |
| `:q`            | Quit                                                                |
| `:wq`           | Save and quit                                                       |
| `:q!`           | Quit without saving changes                                         |
| `:e filename`   | Edit another file                                                   |
| `:r filename`   | Read (insert) another file at the cursor                            |
| `:s/old/new/`   | Substitute first occurrence of ‚Äúold‚Äù with ‚Äúnew‚Äù in the current line |
| `:%s/old/new/g` | Substitute all occurrences in the file                              |
| `:/pattern`     | Jump to line containing pattern                                     |
| `:set number`   | Show line numbers                                                   |












